\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Then,
 we can copy the proof of Theorem 2.13 to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\class{HOD}(T)$
\end_inset

 is closed under comprehension as follows:
 Given a formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x,\vec{y})$
\end_inset

,
 we produce a formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(u,x,z)$
\end_inset

 such that,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1},\dots,w_{k}$
\end_inset

 are parameters in 
\begin_inset Formula $\class{HOD}(T)$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\class{HOD}(T)$
\end_inset

,
 we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\left(\class{Ord}\cup T\cup\{T\}\right)^{<\omega}$
\end_inset

 such that there is exactly one set 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(u,x,\vec{w})$
\end_inset

,
 and this set is 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{y\in x\mid\varphi^{\class{HOD}(T)}(y,\vec{w})\}$
\end_inset

.
 The formula is simply:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(u,x,z)\equiv\forall_{y}\left(y\in u\leftrightarrow\exists_{\vec{w}}\left[y\in x\land\varphi^{\class{HOD}(T)}(y,\vec{w})\land\Phi(w_{1},z^{(1)})\land\dots\Phi(w_{n},z^{(n)})\right]\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{(n)}$
\end_inset

